03:32.253 --> 03:34.046
(pop music)

03:38.426 --> 03:39.718
(distant honking)

03:39.844 --> 03:41.845
(dialing)

03:44.557 --> 03:46.058
(ringing)

03:46.976 --> 03:48.268
(cellphone ringing)

03:50.855 --> 03:53.565
(ringing)
(beeping)

03:53.691 --> 03:55.734
- Yes?

03:55.860 --> 03:58.403
<i>(woman): Collect call from Zoe.
Will you accept the charges?</i>

03:58.529 --> 04:00.989
- Yes, I'll... accept the charges.

04:01.157 --> 04:03.283
<i>(girl): Daddy? It's me.
How are you doing?</i>

04:03.409 --> 04:05.744
<i>- Hi! Fine.
- That's great.</i>

04:05.870 --> 04:06.870
(brushing)

04:06.996 --> 04:08.956
<i>Where are you?
What's that sound?</i>

04:09.123 --> 04:11.291
- I'm in a carwash.

04:11.417 --> 04:15.337
- Wow! I've never talked to you
when you've been in a carwash before.

04:15.463 --> 04:17.297
Μake sure you've got
all the windows rolled up.

04:17.464 --> 04:20.341
Remember the time that...
that we were in the carwash,

04:20.468 --> 04:23.595
and I started playing
with the automatic window?

04:23.721 --> 04:26.306
How old was I, Daddy?
5 or 6?

04:26.474 --> 04:28.976
<i>I got absolutely soaked, remember?</i>

04:29.143 --> 04:30.978
- Why are you calling me, Zoe?

04:31.145 --> 04:34.022
<i>- Why am I calling you?
You're my father.</i>

04:34.440 --> 04:36.733
What, I'm not supposed to call you?

04:36.859 --> 04:39.111
What's... what's the matter with
wanting to talk to you, Daddy?

04:39.237 --> 04:41.989
- Nothing's wrong with trying
to talk to me, Zoe.

04:42.115 --> 04:43.907
<i>- Then what's the problem?</i>

04:44.033 --> 04:45.325
- The problem is...

04:47.537 --> 04:50.289
The problem is I don't know
who I'm talking to right now.

04:50.707 --> 04:52.916
- Oh, 'cause you think I'm stoned,
Daddy?

04:53.042 --> 04:56.044
Is that what you're thinking?
I've got a needle stuck in my arm?

04:56.212 --> 04:59.381
<i>Are you thinking that I've scored, Daddy,
that I'm calling you for money?</i>

04:59.549 --> 05:02.968
That I'm begging?
God, I don't fucking believe this.

05:03.136 --> 05:06.763
<i>Daddy, are you listening to me?!
Daddy!</i>

05:07.056 --> 05:08.432
Daddy!

05:11.185 --> 05:12.602
- Yes...

05:12.687 --> 05:14.604
<i>- Why can't you talk to me?</i>

05:17.984 --> 05:21.194
- Because I need to know
what state you're in, Zoe...

05:21.279 --> 05:23.947
before I know how to talk to you.

05:24.157 --> 05:26.158
(man): Come on, let's go.

05:26.326 --> 05:27.617
- Daddy!

05:28.369 --> 05:29.953
(engine starting)

05:33.750 --> 05:35.667
(distant police siren blaring)

05:38.004 --> 05:40.339
(soft country music)

05:54.604 --> 05:57.272
<i>Speak a little softer</i>

05:57.357 --> 05:59.775
<i>And wink a little louder</i>

05:59.942 --> 06:03.820
<i>And shoot less with more care</i>

06:05.323 --> 06:07.574
<i>And sing a little sweeter</i>

06:07.700 --> 06:10.535
<i>And love a little longer</i>

06:10.661 --> 06:15.582
<i>And soon you will be there</i>

06:15.708 --> 06:18.794
<i>Here</i>

06:18.920 --> 06:22.464
<i>All we have here is sky</i>

06:23.966 --> 06:28.178
<i>All the sky is
is blue</i>

06:29.764 --> 06:31.640
<i>All the blue is</i>

06:31.766 --> 06:37.020
<i>Is one more colour</i>

06:37.563 --> 06:48.448
<i>One more colour</i>

06:48.574 --> 06:51.868
<i>Now</i>

06:53.996 --> 06:55.789
- Well, that was great.
- Really?

06:55.915 --> 06:58.125
- You're gonna blow
everyone away.

06:58.251 --> 06:59.376
- You mean it?
- Of course.

06:59.502 --> 07:01.753
- You don't sound like...
completely sure.

07:01.879 --> 07:03.755
(indistinct chatter)
- I am.

07:03.881 --> 07:07.300
Really.

07:09.220 --> 07:10.762
It was awesome.

07:11.848 --> 07:14.433
(chuckling)
- I'm so happy, Daddy.

07:16.352 --> 07:18.770
(mooing)

07:19.272 --> 07:21.314
Let's get some ice cream, Daddy.

07:25.403 --> 07:27.487
(persistent honking)

07:34.495 --> 07:36.580
(dialing)

07:36.706 --> 07:38.623
<i>(ringing)</i>

07:38.749 --> 07:40.709
- Operator, can you hear me?

07:40.835 --> 07:42.335
(woman): Yes, go ahead, please.

07:42.462 --> 07:46.715
- Um... I-I seem to be
in a strange situation.

07:46.841 --> 07:48.717
I'm-I'm calling from my car.

07:48.843 --> 07:51.219
And I appear to be stuck
in a carwash.

07:51.345 --> 07:52.220
<i>- A carwash?</i>

07:52.346 --> 07:54.222
- Right. Yeah, a carwash.
Uh...

07:54.348 --> 07:57.350
<i>- Can you speak a little louder,
please, sir?</i>

07:57.435 --> 07:59.853
<i>Sorry, sir. I'm losing you again.</i>

08:00.771 --> 08:02.105
(phone beeping)

08:04.525 --> 08:05.567
(ignition signal beeping)

08:08.529 --> 08:19.873
(grunting)

08:22.293 --> 08:23.793
- Jesus...

08:25.379 --> 08:26.463
(grunting)

08:28.341 --> 08:30.800
(electro-acoustic music)

09:34.991 --> 09:36.616
<i>(children screaming)</i>

09:39.996 --> 09:42.080
(background chatter)

09:48.337 --> 09:49.671
(woman): Okay, here we are!

09:49.839 --> 09:52.215
Everybody out!

09:52.842 --> 09:55.552
Come on! Quickly now.

09:55.678 --> 09:58.847
Gather around.
Come on, everybody.

09:58.889 --> 10:02.225
Come out quickly.
We haven't got all day.

10:02.893 --> 10:04.269
Now, I want you to listen to me.
- What is it?

10:04.395 --> 10:06.479
(woman): I got a few things
I have to tell you.

10:06.606 --> 10:08.607
- Just the way Dolores gets so excited
with the kids.

10:08.733 --> 10:11.526
- Alright. Rule number 1.
- It's like the biggest thing in her life.

10:11.652 --> 10:13.945
- Don't stick your fingers
into any of the cages.

10:14.071 --> 10:17.991
Heidi, this applies to you.
And Shane, get back here, please.

10:18.284 --> 10:20.619
I don't care how cute
some of these animals may be,

10:20.745 --> 10:22.829
the fact is
they don't like being here.

10:23.039 --> 10:25.874
No matter how many ribbons
they may have won. Eh?

10:26.000 --> 10:27.417
(indistinct chatter)

10:27.543 --> 10:29.461
Rule number 2.
Hey, Sam.

10:29.587 --> 10:33.131
Hey, Nicole.
Rule number 2: no kicking,

10:33.257 --> 10:35.550
pushing, shoving or biting.

10:35.718 --> 10:38.553
Rule number 3: older kids,
you look after the younger kids.

10:38.721 --> 10:42.557
If any of you get lost, you come here
to the red lady. I will find you.

10:42.725 --> 10:45.268
Rule number 4: wiggle your noses
and have fun.

10:45.394 --> 10:47.354
(distant barking)

11:11.754 --> 11:13.838
(TV playing)

11:18.678 --> 11:20.428
(shivering)

11:27.770 --> 11:38.405
(dinging)

11:40.616 --> 11:41.950
- Hello.

11:42.076 --> 11:43.910
(toilet flushing)

11:46.330 --> 11:48.248
- Is it raining outside?

11:48.332 --> 11:51.000
- No, uh... had an accident.

11:51.168 --> 11:53.169
Do you have a room?

11:56.340 --> 11:58.675
- Will you be spending
more than a night?

11:58.843 --> 12:00.760
- Hard to say. Uh...

12:00.845 --> 12:03.346
Could have some business here-
- You a reporter?

12:10.646 --> 12:12.230
- No, sir.

12:16.444 --> 12:18.486
- You here about the accident?

12:18.612 --> 12:20.488
- Yes.

12:20.614 --> 12:22.574
I'm a lawyer.

12:23.993 --> 12:27.036
I realize this is an awful time,
but it's important that we talk.

12:29.623 --> 12:31.416
- Kyle Lansdom's a drunk.

12:31.542 --> 12:33.418
Nobody likes him.

12:33.544 --> 12:36.588
He's a nasty piece of work.
- In what way?

12:36.714 --> 12:40.216
- Well, he's been drinking since high school.
Fucked himself up.

12:41.051 --> 12:42.886
Used to be smart enough.

12:43.012 --> 12:44.596
- Any criminal record?

12:44.722 --> 12:49.976
- Probably... at least half a dozen
traffic convictions, drunk driving.

12:50.102 --> 12:52.896
Lost his licence.
That's why he don't work no more.

12:53.731 --> 12:58.276
Can't get off that... shitty dump
they live on.

12:58.986 --> 13:02.238
Whatever money does come in
goes to booze.

13:02.364 --> 13:04.574
- How does the family survive?

13:06.243 --> 13:07.577
- I dunno.

13:08.245 --> 13:09.579
Church charity...

13:09.705 --> 13:12.749
Welfare, food bank.
They scrape by.

13:13.793 --> 13:15.376
(munching)

13:16.170 --> 13:17.504
(sighing)

13:17.630 --> 13:19.631
- And, uh...

13:20.716 --> 13:23.092
What about Dora?
(woman): Doreen.

13:23.677 --> 13:26.221
She was a friend of mine.

13:27.306 --> 13:29.641
- When was that?
- At school.

13:32.645 --> 13:35.772
She fell for Kyle
just before we graduated.

13:37.608 --> 13:39.526
And... she got pregnant.

13:40.736 --> 13:43.571
Uh... moved into a... a trailer,

13:43.656 --> 13:46.908
up... on a wood lot
Kyle's dad used to own.

13:46.992 --> 13:50.620
Kyle started spending more and more time
at the Spread Eagle.

13:50.746 --> 13:52.664
- That's the local bar?

13:55.584 --> 13:58.837
- Uh... and coming home drunk,
and...

14:00.464 --> 14:03.675
feeling trapped by his life,
I guess, and...

14:04.718 --> 14:07.178
blaming her for that and...

14:07.304 --> 14:10.014
Well.
- And...?

14:10.266 --> 14:12.600
And... and...

14:12.935 --> 14:14.477
and he beat her.

14:15.521 --> 14:17.981
- He beat her?
(man): Yes!

14:18.107 --> 14:19.315
- Oh...

14:19.859 --> 14:23.486
You see... to do this right,

14:23.612 --> 14:25.196
to actually have a chance
of winning,

14:25.322 --> 14:28.658
of getting some money to compensate you
for the loss of your boy,

14:31.328 --> 14:33.288
we need folks like you.

14:33.455 --> 14:36.040
Sensitive, loving parents,

14:36.166 --> 14:38.960
with no criminal background,
no history of trouble in the town.

14:39.086 --> 14:42.255
Do you understand?
- Yes.

14:42.381 --> 14:45.383
- Now, of these people
that you've told me about

14:45.509 --> 14:48.428
whose kids were killed,

14:48.554 --> 14:51.723
who do you consider to be good,
upstanding neighbours?

14:52.600 --> 14:55.518
People who will help us
in our cause?

14:55.644 --> 14:59.272
- Uh, there's the Hamiltons.
Joe and Shelly Hamilton.

14:59.398 --> 15:01.316
(man): Oh yeah, right!

15:01.442 --> 15:02.817
(scoffing)

15:04.987 --> 15:08.114
Everybody knows that Joey

15:08.240 --> 15:11.075
steals antiques from summer cottages

15:11.243 --> 15:13.494
and sells them to dealers
in the city.

15:13.621 --> 15:16.331
He's been doing that for years.
- That's great, Wendell.

15:16.457 --> 15:19.083
That's exactly what I need to know.

15:19.251 --> 15:21.461
You see, so it won't come back
to haunt our case later on-

15:21.587 --> 15:23.796
(woman): There's the Prescotts.

15:23.923 --> 15:27.091
- Oh! You know how much money
he owes to the bank?

15:27.217 --> 15:28.635
He's about to lose his house,

15:28.761 --> 15:30.678
he's about to lose his car.
- Yeah.

15:30.804 --> 15:31.721
But Charlene, she-

15:31.847 --> 15:35.016
- Charlene is over at the Spread Eagle
every other night.

15:35.142 --> 15:38.478
She sleeps with whoever
she can get her hands on.

15:38.646 --> 15:40.271
I mean, she'd go down for a...

15:40.397 --> 15:42.565
pat on the head
and a fistful of peanuts.

15:42.691 --> 15:44.150
- Ah... Ahem!

15:50.991 --> 15:53.993
- Forget the Atwaters and the Biladows.
They're all inbred.

15:54.828 --> 15:55.870
- Oh.

15:55.996 --> 15:58.331
(woman): The Ottos.
- The...

16:02.503 --> 16:04.671
- Well, tell me about the Ottos.

16:04.755 --> 16:07.340
- Wanda and Hartley.

16:07.508 --> 16:09.842
They lost Bear.

16:10.010 --> 16:12.178
He was their adopted son.

16:14.181 --> 16:17.517
He was a beautiful boy.
He was Indian.

16:18.185 --> 16:21.521
- That's good.
Judges like adopted Indian boys.

16:21.605 --> 16:24.232
Tell me more about the Ottos.
- They're smart.

16:25.693 --> 16:27.443
They've been to college.

16:27.569 --> 16:30.321
They moved here from the city
about a dozen years ago.

16:30.447 --> 16:31.906
(man): What do they do?

16:32.032 --> 16:34.659
- Crafts.
(Wendell scoffing)

16:34.785 --> 16:35.910
(man scribbling)

16:36.036 --> 16:37.954
Wanda does these photographic things.

16:38.163 --> 16:41.958
That's one of hers.
Right here on the wall.

16:42.960 --> 16:46.212
- You know, they probably smoke weed.
- You don't know that.

16:46.296 --> 16:48.214
- They ever been busted?

16:48.340 --> 16:50.216
- No.
- You don't know!

16:50.300 --> 16:52.885
That's what it is.
You don't know.

16:54.847 --> 16:56.806
(cellphone ringing)

16:58.726 --> 17:00.685
(ringing)
- I'm sorry. Excuse me.

17:00.769 --> 17:02.770
(sighing): Yes?

17:02.896 --> 17:04.731
<i>(woman): Collect call from Zoe.
Will you accept the charges?</i>

17:04.857 --> 17:06.482
- Yes, I'll accept the charges.

17:06.608 --> 17:08.401
Do you mind if I step outside
for a moment?

17:08.527 --> 17:10.737
It's a private call.
I'm so sorry.

17:12.406 --> 17:14.156
(sighing)

17:15.117 --> 17:17.076
- Why do you say things
when you don't know...

17:17.202 --> 17:19.746
- Zoe? Where are you, darling?
(Wendell): Shut up.

17:19.872 --> 17:21.329
(woman): I won't shut up.
- Yeah...

17:21.457 --> 17:23.415
(indistinct comment)
(Wendell): Oh, shut up.

17:23.541 --> 17:25.460
- Yeah...
(Wendell): Shut up!

17:25.586 --> 17:28.463
- Yes, I am listening...
(Wendell): Shut your big, fat mouth.

17:29.840 --> 17:33.468
- Oh... no, of course I'm being sincere.
I understand what you're saying.

17:33.594 --> 17:34.927
The fact that you...
(shouting)

17:35.054 --> 17:37.889
The fact that you like the doctor,
I mean... it's half the battle...

17:38.015 --> 17:39.557
(Wendell): Shut up.
(woman): You're jealous again.

17:39.683 --> 17:41.726
- Please...
(Wendell): Shut up. I'm jealous of what?

17:41.852 --> 17:44.187
What am I jealous of?
(woman): 'Cause he's smarter than you.

17:44.313 --> 17:45.563
- Yeah...
(Wendell): Smarter than me?

17:45.689 --> 17:48.107
Oh, yeah!
Like the Ottos are smart, too.

17:48.233 --> 17:50.151
Did you hear what that man said?
He said, "Good, Wendell."

17:50.277 --> 17:52.361
Good! He said, "Good!"
- I will do it in 10 minutes.

17:52.488 --> 17:54.447
(woman): You're a big baby!
(Wendell): Shut up!

18:01.163 --> 18:04.123
(TV sound coming on and off)

18:06.168 --> 18:08.169
(erratic dialogue in headphones)

18:13.050 --> 18:14.634
(exasperated sighing)

18:16.053 --> 18:17.845
(beeping stewardess)

18:18.597 --> 18:20.098
(curtains opening)

18:21.141 --> 18:23.309
- Yes, sir?
- Oh, hi.

18:23.435 --> 18:25.311
I... I can't get any sound of out this.

18:25.437 --> 18:27.355
- Oh, here. I'll get you another pair.
- Thank you.

18:30.526 --> 18:32.527
- Here, you can have mine.

18:35.155 --> 18:38.116
Allison O'Donnell.
- Alli...

18:38.200 --> 18:40.118
- I was a friend of Zoe's.

18:40.202 --> 18:43.121
We used to go to school together.
I used to come to your house.

18:43.205 --> 18:46.707
- Yeah...
- Ally. Μy nickname was Ally.

18:46.834 --> 18:49.335
- Ally? Right, right.

18:49.962 --> 18:51.337
- How are you?

18:52.089 --> 18:53.339
- Oh, I'm just fine.

18:53.465 --> 18:55.550
How about you?
- I'm fine.

18:55.676 --> 18:59.178
I'm... still working with my father.
- Right.

18:59.304 --> 19:01.180
Um...

19:01.348 --> 19:03.516
What does he do again?

19:03.684 --> 19:06.227
- Well, he used to work with you.
You guys used to be partners.

19:06.353 --> 19:08.229
(both chuckling)

19:08.355 --> 19:10.648
- Allison!
- Μm-hmm.

19:10.774 --> 19:12.650
How's Μrs. Stevens?

19:12.776 --> 19:16.279
- Well, she's just fine. She...
We're... not together anymore.

19:16.405 --> 19:18.698
- Yeah, I'd heard that. But she's well?
- Yeah.

19:18.824 --> 19:20.700
- And Zoe?

19:20.826 --> 19:22.535
How's Zoe?

19:22.661 --> 19:23.995
(curtains opening)

19:24.955 --> 19:27.665
(woman): Oh, you've beat me to it.
Here you go.

19:27.791 --> 19:29.417
- Thanks.

19:32.212 --> 19:34.297
(Stevens sighing)
(curtains closing)

19:34.423 --> 19:36.299
(soft music)

19:49.813 --> 19:52.356
(crowing)

19:53.108 --> 19:55.443
(man humming)

20:01.158 --> 20:03.534
(Dolores): 'Μorning, Wanda!
Hey, Hartley!

20:03.660 --> 20:05.953
(Wanda): Hi, Dolores.
(Hartley): Good morning, Dolores.

20:06.330 --> 20:08.539
Beautiful snow we're having,
eh, Dolores?

20:08.707 --> 20:11.584
- Oh, it's just a flurry, Hartley.
It's totally clear up ahead.

20:11.710 --> 20:13.586
- That's good.
(Bear): Look!

20:13.837 --> 20:16.547
(Dolores): What's that you got there?
- What do you think?

20:16.673 --> 20:19.550
(Dolores): Well, it's, uh...
certainly what you call interesting.

20:20.594 --> 20:21.928
- You hate it.

20:22.262 --> 20:25.056
(Hartley laughing)
- No. No, no. I didn't say that. No.

20:25.182 --> 20:27.934
(Wanda): I could wrap it up
to protect the children.

20:28.060 --> 20:29.560
- I can just strap up on the roof, eh?

20:29.686 --> 20:31.729
(Hartley): There's an idea!
- Come on, give me a break!

20:31.855 --> 20:33.773
It's for the school bazaar.

20:33.899 --> 20:35.900
- Oh, well, it's bizarre alright.
(laughing)

20:36.026 --> 20:37.735
Come on, Bear.
Let's get you outta here.

20:37.861 --> 20:40.613
- Come on, Bear.
Away from your crazy mother.

20:40.948 --> 20:43.616
- That's right. I'll see you, Wanda.
Bye, Hartley.

20:43.951 --> 20:45.701
(Wanda): Take care.
(Hartley): So long.

20:50.123 --> 20:51.540
Bye-bye!

20:52.125 --> 20:53.876
(soft medieval music)

21:01.551 --> 21:04.637
<i>(Dolores): The Ottos always waited
for the bus with Bear.</i>

21:05.639 --> 21:08.766
<i>They were the only parents who...
who did that.</i>

21:09.685 --> 21:12.645
<i>Together, like that.</i>

21:13.814 --> 21:16.315
Uh, I guess they were
what you might call...

21:19.236 --> 21:20.486
hi... hippies.

21:21.863 --> 21:23.656
- What do you mean by that,
Μrs. Driscoll?

21:23.865 --> 21:25.908
- Dolores.

21:26.034 --> 21:29.328
No one... ever calls me Μrs. Driscoll.

21:30.122 --> 21:32.206
- What do you mean by that,
Dolores?

21:32.332 --> 21:34.709
- Uh, about the Ottos?
- Yes.

21:34.876 --> 21:37.503
What exactly do you mean
by hippies?

21:38.130 --> 21:39.714
(distant barking)

21:42.551 --> 21:44.552
- I... mean the way they look.

21:46.555 --> 21:49.515
<i>Their hair, and... clothing.</i>

21:51.018 --> 21:52.935
<i>(Stevens): Do they have any reputation
for drugs?</i>

21:53.061 --> 21:57.606
<i>(Dolores): Oh... no, no, no.
Nothing like that. No, uh...</i>

21:57.733 --> 21:59.942
<i>No, the Ottos...
(laughing)</i>

22:00.152 --> 22:02.778
...are what I would call...

22:02.904 --> 22:05.656
uh... model citizens.

22:05.782 --> 22:06.073
(distant barking)

22:06.199 --> 22:08.534
They're regular at town meetings.

22:08.702 --> 22:11.370
They, uh... give their opinion

22:11.580 --> 22:14.373
in a respectful way.

22:14.541 --> 22:16.375
And they, uh...

22:16.543 --> 22:20.796
they help out at various...
(Dolores inhaling)

22:21.089 --> 22:23.341
...fundraising bazaars,

22:23.467 --> 22:24.759
though they aren't...

22:27.846 --> 22:29.722
Uh...
(Dolores gulping)

22:31.391 --> 22:33.893
...church goers.

22:34.186 --> 22:36.562
- Μm...

22:36.646 --> 22:39.398
And they love Bear?
(Dolores): Oh... yes.

22:40.442 --> 22:42.568
It's... it's like
he's their little treasure.

22:42.652 --> 22:45.237
He's such a beautiful boy...

22:45.322 --> 22:48.199
Oh, well, there's a picture of him
