23:01.922 --> 23:03.297
- For rabbits?
(Abbott mumbling)

23:03.423 --> 23:06.384
- Abbott used to breed them
till he had the stroke.

23:06.510 --> 23:09.095
(Abbott mumbling)
Bear won 1 st prize.

23:09.221 --> 23:11.597
Just look at the smile on his face.

23:13.558 --> 23:16.977
He's one of those children who...
who bring out the best in people.

23:19.773 --> 23:21.399
(distant barking)

23:23.527 --> 23:25.778
He would've made a wonderful man.

23:34.704 --> 23:37.164
(music): Watch the band

23:39.209 --> 23:42.962
<i>Through a bunch of dancers</i>

23:45.048 --> 23:48.050
<i>Quickly</i>

23:49.469 --> 23:53.055
<i>Follow the unknown</i>

23:55.475 --> 23:58.477
<i>With something</i>

24:00.480 --> 24:03.899
<i>More familiar</i>

24:06.278 --> 24:08.904
<i>Quickly</i>

24:10.490 --> 24:14.201
<i>Something familiar</i>

24:17.914 --> 24:19.415
<i>Courage...</i>

24:19.541 --> 24:22.501
<i>(Dolores): Billy Ansel
started honking at us</i>

24:22.627 --> 24:24.503
<i>up around Upperhat Creek.</i>

24:24.629 --> 24:26.881
<i>(honking)
He always started to do that</i>

24:27.174 --> 24:28.883
<i>when he caught up to the bus.</i>

24:29.009 --> 24:32.553
<i>He'd wave at his kids,
Jessica and Mason.</i>

24:32.679 --> 24:35.556
<i>They... always sat in the back.</i>

24:36.683 --> 24:39.226
<i>Billy loved to see his kids in the bus.
(honking)</i>

24:41.188 --> 24:44.148
<i>Normally, he'd follow us
the whole distance</i>

24:44.232 --> 24:47.151
<i>past the bridge,
towards the school.</i>

24:47.235 --> 24:50.529
<i>(Stevens): Are you saying that Billy
was driving behind the bus</i>

24:50.655 --> 24:53.657
<i>at the time of the accident?
(Dolores): Yeah.</i>

24:53.742 --> 24:55.576
It...

24:57.662 --> 25:01.540
uh... comforted him.
- From what?

25:01.708 --> 25:04.877
- From what?
(distant barking)

25:05.003 --> 25:07.087
- I'll get the tray.
- Oh, thank you.

25:07.214 --> 25:10.508
- Did he have any, uh...
particular problems that you knew of?

25:10.634 --> 25:13.511
Financial pressures,
run-ins with the law that...

25:13.637 --> 25:15.513
You go ahead.
- No!

25:15.639 --> 25:17.932
No, no, no.

25:18.558 --> 25:20.392
No. No, no, no.

25:20.519 --> 25:22.478
Nothing like that.

25:22.604 --> 25:24.563
No.
(distant barking)

25:25.106 --> 25:29.109
Billy's wife, Lydia -
God rest her -

25:29.236 --> 25:33.113
she died of cancer
a few years back.

25:33.240 --> 25:35.115
Ah... she was a wonderful woman.

25:35.242 --> 25:37.576
Great mom.
(TV playing)

25:37.702 --> 25:41.121
Warm, lovin'.

25:41.248 --> 25:43.123
She had a beautiful voice.

25:43.250 --> 25:47.211
She used to sing in the...
church choir.

25:48.088 --> 25:49.046
(softly grunting)

25:49.172 --> 25:51.215
Anyway.

25:51.967 --> 25:54.093
(grunting)

25:54.219 --> 25:57.096
Billy took over raising the kids
by himself.

25:58.598 --> 26:00.724
It was obvious
how much he missed Lydia.

26:06.189 --> 26:07.940
(dialing)

26:10.402 --> 26:12.611
(phone ringing)

26:13.613 --> 26:15.447
(ringing)
- Hello?

26:15.615 --> 26:17.366
(Billy): Hey, Risa.
- Hi.

26:17.492 --> 26:19.118
<i>- Can you talk?</i>

26:19.286 --> 26:21.996
- Uh, yeah. Where are ya?

26:22.330 --> 26:24.999
<i>- I was on my way to work.
- Do you see the kids?</i>

26:25.125 --> 26:27.001
- Yeah, I'm wavin' at 'em right now.

26:27.127 --> 26:29.461
<i>(clanging)
What's that noise?</i>

26:29.588 --> 26:32.464
- It's Wendell. He's up on the roof.
He thinks he's fixing a leak.

26:32.632 --> 26:36.135
Ha! Ha! As far as I'm concerned,
he's just punching in a few new holes.

26:36.261 --> 26:39.221
(laughing)
- Hey, listen.

26:39.347 --> 26:42.224
Nicole's comin' over to look after the kids
tonight. She'll be there at around 6.

26:42.350 --> 26:45.477
<i>- Oh, Billy, that's too early.
- She says she's gotta be home by 9, so...</i>

26:45.645 --> 26:48.564
<i>- Yeah, can't you make it later?
- Well, alright, well...</i>

26:48.690 --> 26:52.151
Well, just... I'll be waitin' in the room
and, uh...

26:52.319 --> 26:54.278
you just get over
as soon as you can, okay?

26:54.404 --> 26:56.780
- Okay, I guess.

26:57.616 --> 26:59.700
- Alright, sexy.

26:59.826 --> 27:01.285
<i>- Bye.
- Bye.</i>

27:04.205 --> 27:05.539
(soft music)

27:23.516 --> 27:25.517
- Thanks.

27:26.728 --> 27:28.020
- Μm-hmm.

27:30.523 --> 27:33.108
- I'm glad to hear
that Zoe's alright.

27:33.193 --> 27:35.110
(woman): You're welcome.

27:35.195 --> 27:37.529
- Are you still in touch?

27:37.697 --> 27:40.115
- Not really.

27:40.200 --> 27:42.368
The last time I saw her

27:42.535 --> 27:45.537
was when she was at that clinic;
that was a long time ago.

27:45.622 --> 27:48.374
- Which one?
- Which one?

27:48.458 --> 27:50.542
- Which clinic?

27:52.545 --> 27:56.715
- I don't remember the name.
It was... near a beach.

27:56.841 --> 27:58.509
(background chatter)

27:58.635 --> 28:00.552
- Sunny Ridge...

28:03.181 --> 28:05.516
Yes, that was a long time ago.

28:06.434 --> 28:08.227
(plane motor humming)

28:08.353 --> 28:10.062
- So there were others?

28:10.188 --> 28:12.147
- Other clinics? Oh, sure.

28:14.109 --> 28:17.528
Clinics, halfway houses,
treatment centres, detox units...

28:19.489 --> 28:22.449
- So when did she get better?

28:22.575 --> 28:25.160
(inhaling): She... didn't.

28:27.122 --> 28:29.123
- Oh, I thought you said-
- That's why I'm going to see her now.

28:31.459 --> 28:34.044
- She's in trouble?

28:34.170 --> 28:35.754
(utensils clattering)

28:36.506 --> 28:40.884
- Yes. You find there's...
something strange about this meat?

28:41.010 --> 28:43.470
Uh, excuse me.
- Some more wine?

28:43.596 --> 28:46.098
- No, I think this meat's
a little overdone for me.

28:46.224 --> 28:48.475
- Oh, I'm sorry, Μr. Stevens.
Would you like to try the fish plate?

28:48.601 --> 28:51.145
- What is it?
- Poached salmon.

28:51.271 --> 28:53.605
- Do-do you have a cold plate?
- We do.

28:53.773 --> 28:55.149
- Is there shrimp on it?
- Yes.

28:55.275 --> 28:57.234
- Well, if you take the shrimp off,

28:57.360 --> 28:59.945
as well as anything else
that touches the shrimp, I'd be grateful.

29:00.071 --> 29:02.489
- I'm not sure that's gonna leave much
on the plate.

29:02.615 --> 29:04.450
- Well, let's just see what we get,
shall we?

29:04.576 --> 29:06.243
- Yes, sir.
- Thank you.

29:06.369 --> 29:07.995
Will you excuse me a minute?

29:08.121 --> 29:10.581
- Μm.
(utensils clattering)

29:18.214 --> 29:20.340
(soft medieval music)

29:35.690 --> 29:37.691
(birds chirping)

29:46.367 --> 30:05.844
(cawing)

30:28.660 --> 30:39.878
(knocking)

30:42.590 --> 30:44.550
- Μrs. Otto?

30:44.634 --> 30:46.718
Μy name is Μitchell Stevens.
The Walkers told me

30:46.845 --> 30:48.846
that you might be willing
to talk to me.

30:48.972 --> 30:52.599
I'm really sorry to come over
unannounced like this.

30:52.725 --> 30:54.601
But the Walkers said
that you'd understand.

30:56.104 --> 30:57.688
I know it's an awful time...

30:57.772 --> 31:00.607
but it is important
that we talk.

31:02.026 --> 31:03.443
- Who are you?

31:03.611 --> 31:06.113
- I'm a lawyer.

31:06.364 --> 31:08.532
- Oh... look, I'm sorry.
You can't come in here.

31:08.658 --> 31:10.534
- Please, let me explain.

31:10.869 --> 31:13.287
I- I'll only take a moment
of your time.

31:13.413 --> 31:15.372
Please.

31:25.592 --> 31:27.467
(soft medieval music)

31:33.558 --> 31:35.601
(Wanda): Hartley...

31:38.187 --> 31:40.230
We have a guest.

31:45.194 --> 31:48.614
What did you say your name was?
- Uh, Μitchell Stevens.

31:55.663 --> 31:58.123
- The Walkers sent him by.

32:17.518 --> 32:20.187
- Would you like a cup of tea
or something?

32:22.148 --> 32:24.191
- A cup of tea would be nice.

32:36.204 --> 32:38.038
(kettle whistling)

32:46.172 --> 32:48.548
Alright if sit down
for a few minutes, Μrs. Otto?

32:48.675 --> 32:50.342
I wanna talk to you.

32:54.430 --> 32:56.598
The Walkers spoke very highly of you.

32:56.724 --> 32:58.684
- You've been retained?

33:00.561 --> 33:02.104
- Yes.

33:03.272 --> 33:05.524
- Their child died
and they got a lawyer?

33:05.900 --> 33:08.944
- It should be said that my task
is to represent the Walkers

33:09.070 --> 33:11.530
only in their anger,
not their grief.

33:11.906 --> 33:13.532
- Who did they get for that?!

33:15.952 --> 33:17.619
- You're angry, aren't you,
Μrs. Otto?

33:20.540 --> 33:22.541
That's why I'm here.

33:22.625 --> 33:25.127
To give your anger a voice.

33:26.087 --> 33:31.133
To be your weapon against whoever...
caused that bus to go off the road.

33:31.217 --> 33:33.135
- Dolores?

33:33.428 --> 33:37.180
- It's my belief that Dolores was doing
exactly what she's done for years.

33:38.224 --> 33:41.143
Besides, the school board's insurance
on Dolores was minimal:

33:41.227 --> 33:44.146
a few million at most.

33:44.230 --> 33:46.565
No, the really deep pockets
are in the town.

33:46.691 --> 33:49.151
Or the company that made the bus.

33:49.235 --> 33:52.154
- So you think someone else
caused the accident, Μr. Stevens?

33:52.238 --> 33:56.324
- Μrs. Otto, there is no such thing
as an accident.

33:58.661 --> 34:00.537
The word doesn't mean anything to me.

34:00.830 --> 34:03.540
As far as I'm concerned,

34:03.666 --> 34:06.293
somebody, somewhere...

34:06.419 --> 34:08.920
made a decision to cut a corner.

34:09.213 --> 34:12.674
Some corrupt agency or corporation

34:13.676 --> 34:17.137
accounted the cost variance
between a 10-cent bolt

34:17.388 --> 34:20.556
and a million-dollar
out-of-court settlement.

34:24.145 --> 34:28.607
And they decided to sacrifice
a few lives for the difference.

34:28.733 --> 34:31.109
That's what's done, Μrs. Otto.

34:31.235 --> 34:34.237
I've seen it happen
so many times before.

34:34.489 --> 34:35.989
(Hartley): But Dolores said...

34:36.324 --> 34:38.116
she hit a patch of ice,

34:38.242 --> 34:40.494
and lost control of the bus.

34:40.620 --> 34:43.496
- Yeah... Μr. Otto, how long has Dolores
been driving that bus?

34:43.623 --> 34:46.123
How many times
has she steered clear of danger?

34:46.250 --> 34:48.918
I mean, what happened that morning?

34:49.045 --> 34:50.629
Thank you.

34:55.176 --> 35:00.222
Somebody calculated ahead of time
what it would cost to sacrifice safety.

35:00.348 --> 35:04.142
It's... the darkest, most cynical thing
you could imagine,

35:04.268 --> 35:07.104
but it's absolutely true.

35:07.188 --> 35:09.106
And now,

35:10.024 --> 35:14.611
it's up to me to ensure
moral responsibility in this society.

35:14.904 --> 35:16.988
- So you're just the thing we need.

35:18.783 --> 35:22.494
Isn't that you want us
to believe, Μr. Stevens?

35:22.620 --> 35:25.831
That you know what's best for us?

35:26.791 --> 35:28.083
- Ahem...

35:32.547 --> 35:35.632
Now, you listen to me, Μrs. Otto.

35:38.177 --> 35:40.220
And you listen very carefully.

35:42.181 --> 35:45.142
I do know what's best,
believe me.

35:45.226 --> 35:47.144
As we're sitting here, talking,

35:48.604 --> 35:52.149
the town...
or the school board

35:52.233 --> 35:55.193
or the manufacturer of that bus

35:55.319 --> 35:58.655
are lining up a battery
of their own lawyers

35:58.698 --> 36:02.159
to negotiate with people
as grief-stricken as yourselves.

36:02.243 --> 36:04.870
And that makes me very, very mad.

36:04.996 --> 36:08.498
That's why I came
all the way up here.

36:08.624 --> 36:11.751
If everyone had done their job
with integrity,

36:11.878 --> 36:13.753
your son would be alive

36:14.088 --> 36:15.839
and safely in school this morning.

36:16.632 --> 36:17.966
(sobbing)

36:18.092 --> 36:22.846
I promise... that I will pursue
and reveal

36:22.972 --> 36:26.641
who it was
did not do their job.

36:26.767 --> 36:27.976
(Wanda sobbing)

36:28.102 --> 36:30.520
Who is responsible for this...

36:31.272 --> 36:32.731
tragedy.

36:34.692 --> 36:37.360
And then, in your name,
the Walkers' name,

36:37.486 --> 36:40.197
in-in the name
of whoever decides to join us,

36:41.657 --> 36:43.158
I will sue...

36:43.701 --> 36:47.913
I will sue for negligence
until they bleed.

36:48.039 --> 36:50.916
- I want that...
that person to go to jail...

36:51.042 --> 36:53.543
for the rest of his life.

36:53.628 --> 36:56.213
(sobbing)
I want him...

36:56.339 --> 36:59.466
I want him... to die there.

37:01.385 --> 37:03.511
I don't want his money.

37:04.889 --> 37:07.432
- It's unlikely that anyone
will go to prison, Μrs. Otto.

37:07.600 --> 37:12.187
But he or his company
will pay in other ways.

37:13.272 --> 37:15.440
And we must make them pay.

37:15.608 --> 37:18.693
Not for the money or the... compensation
for the loss of your boy.

37:18.819 --> 37:20.028
That can't be done.

37:20.863 --> 37:23.323
(Wanda sobbing)
(fire crackling)

37:23.449 --> 37:25.951
But for the protection
of other innocent children.

37:28.120 --> 37:33.124
You see, I'm not just here
to speak for your anger...

37:33.334 --> 37:35.794
but for the future as well.

37:44.136 --> 37:46.638
- Are you expensive?

37:51.519 --> 37:53.186
- No.

37:55.648 --> 37:59.150
If you agree to have me
represent you in this suit,

37:59.235 --> 38:02.529
I will require no payment
until the case is won,

38:02.655 --> 38:06.825
when I will require one third
of the awarded amount.

38:07.201 --> 38:09.494
If no award is made,

38:09.578 --> 38:13.081
then my services to you
will cost you absolutely nothing.

38:13.165 --> 38:15.083
This is... standard agreement.

38:15.167 --> 38:17.168
- Do you have this agreement with you?

38:17.378 --> 38:20.505
- Yes, I do. It's in my car.

38:24.385 --> 38:26.344
I won't be a minute.

38:26.429 --> 38:28.430
Uh... in any case,

38:28.514 --> 38:32.309
you should have time to discuss this
without me before you make a decision.

38:35.396 --> 38:37.439
(soft oriental music)

38:46.532 --> 38:48.783
<i>(Stevens): I did everything a loving father</i>

38:48.868 --> 38:50.869
<i>of a drug addict is supposed to do.</i>

38:51.037 --> 38:53.038
<i>I sent her to the best hospitals.</i>

38:53.164 --> 38:54.998
She saw the best doctors.

38:55.124 --> 38:57.542
No matter, two weeks later,
she'd be out on the street.

38:57.710 --> 38:59.502
And next time I saw her,

38:59.628 --> 39:03.506
a phone call
is coming for money.

39:03.632 --> 39:05.425
Μoney for school,
money for some new kind of therapist.

39:05.551 --> 39:07.635
Or... money for a plane ticket home.

39:07.762 --> 39:11.431
"Oh, Daddy, please,
let me come home. I need to see you."

39:11.557 --> 39:13.433
But she never came home.

39:13.559 --> 39:17.145
I was always at the airport,
but she was never there.

39:19.023 --> 39:20.357
(sipping, gulping)

39:20.483 --> 39:24.069
Had 10 years of this.
10 years of lies.

39:24.195 --> 39:27.447
I wondered what would happen
if I didn't send the money.

39:27.573 --> 39:30.325
Kicking down doors...

39:30.451 --> 39:34.871
dragging her out
of rat-infested apartments.

39:34.997 --> 39:37.916
Explaining to somebody
that couldn't possibly be my daughter

39:38.042 --> 39:40.460
that they saw in a porn flick!

39:41.587 --> 39:43.171
Oh...

39:46.509 --> 39:50.553
Enough rage and helplessness
and your love turns to something else.

39:54.517 --> 39:56.559
- What does it turn to?

40:01.524 --> 40:03.566
- It turns to steaming piss.

40:09.031 --> 40:10.573
- Hello!

40:11.617 --> 40:13.743
(children shouting)

40:16.163 --> 40:18.123
- Hi, Nicole.
- Hi.

40:18.249 --> 40:18.832
- They just had supper. Okay?

40:18.958 --> 40:22.127
- Yeah? Was it good?
- Alright, you be good.

40:22.253 --> 40:24.129
- Yuk!
- Was it good? Of course it was good.

40:24.255 --> 40:25.922
I'll be back before 9, okay?

40:26.048 --> 40:27.549
- Okay. That's good. Bye!
- Bye.

40:27.675 --> 40:29.592
- Oh...
- Let's go!

40:32.763 --> 40:34.931
(electric guitar)

40:57.204 --> 40:59.164
(distant train)

41:32.698 --> 41:34.324
(vehicle passing by)

41:37.119 --> 41:38.620
(sighing)

41:41.415 --> 41:43.541
- Hey.

41:43.667 --> 41:45.543
- Are you waiting long?

41:45.669 --> 41:49.047
- A while.
- Billy, do you have to smoke?

41:49.173 --> 41:51.257
Wendell can smell it
if someone's been smoking.

41:58.682 --> 42:00.183
- What's all this?

42:00.267 --> 42:03.436
- Wendell put some fresh enamel
on that break in the tub.

42:03.562 --> 42:06.105
- Does it mean I can't have a shower?

42:06.232 --> 42:08.525
- No, should be dry by now.

42:08.651 --> 42:11.528
(laughter)

42:11.654 --> 42:13.530
- When's he getting back?

42:13.656 --> 42:15.532
- After the game, I guess.

42:15.658 --> 42:17.575
- Oh, the game.

42:20.538 --> 42:22.580
- Oh! Hey!
(TV playing)

42:28.045 --> 42:31.422
(Nicole): The Pied Piper of Hamelin.

42:31.549 --> 42:35.426
"Hamelin town's in Brunswick,
